entry.title: Flash Flood Warning issued February 5 at 1:13AM PST until February 5 at 9:00AM PST by NWS Los Angeles/Oxnard CA
entry.summary:
FFWLOX
The National Weather Service in Los Angeles/Oxnard has issued a
* Flash Flood Warning for... The Santa Susana Mountains in western Los Angeles County and eastern Ventura County in southwestern California...
* Until 900 AM PST Monday.
* At 113 AM PST, Doppler radar and rain gauges indicated heavy rain across the warned area. Flash flooding is ongoing or expected to begin shortly.
HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by heavy showers.
SOURCE...Radar and rain gauges.
IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, highways, streets and underpasses as well as other poor drainage and low-lying areas. In addition, landslides are expected.
* Some locations that will experience flash flooding include... eastern Simi Valley, Chatsworth, Santa Clarita, Porter Ranch and Granada Hills.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 4 at 4:43PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A very strong storm will north over the Eastern Bering Sea on Tuesday night and Wednesday. This is expected to bring southerly gales along with snow and blowing snow to the West Coast from the Yukon Delta to the Bering Strait on Tuesday night and Wednesday.
Blizzard conditions are possible with this storm Tuesday afternoon into Wednesday, but it is still uncertain how low visibility will get since the precipitation could be mixed and temperatures will warm to near freezing. There is also still much uncertainty on the track and strength of the storm.
The southerly gales over the Eastern Bering Sea on Tuesday night and Wednesday will bring water levels up 2 to 3 feet from the Bering Strait south, which could cause water to seep up onto the ice along the Coast on Wednesday. No flooding is expected, but this could affect trails that cross ice near the coast from the Bering Strait south.
